        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-09-10 16:21:12.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPavel, Would aaf be properly configured with aai information in HEAT deployment?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "62ee7e9c4e6e2535978c4384a3c9fe4f46a1b625",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 33,
          "name": "James Forsyth",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jf2512@att.com",
          "username": "jimmydot"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-09-10 23:38:44.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis would default HEAT deployments to using AAF, right?  Does it assume one-way-tls in that case?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "92669a7cd5e2d8ec6e16ad4621141ef8f0686da2",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2381,
          "name": "Pavel Paroulek",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pavel.paroulek@orange.com",
          "username": "wageslave"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-09-11 10:33:31.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHarish - a good question. The HEAT deployment is configured with the settings we curretnly have from the AAF. These settings unfortunately have their drawbacks and I predict that most ppl will immidiately turn off AAF as it is more trouble than worth. I have updated the documentation for just such a circumstance https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/How+to+Docker+setup+on+Single+VM",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "d5ef071889bbeed1c415aa3fb9e95ccd08f5499c",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2381,
          "name": "Pavel Paroulek",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pavel.paroulek@orange.com",
          "username": "wageslave"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-09-11 10:44:09.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJimmy - yes the AAF is on by default, that's why I updated our documentation so that people can turn it off again. As for your second question: the AAI clients provide their credentials through http basic auth and the communication is encrypted, in the dev environment with the cert subject: C=US; O=ONAP; OU=aai@aai.onap.org; OU=OSAAF; CN=aai.api.simpledemo.onap.org",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "fafe6870649f3cd8c13bf317458fcee7e6ece254",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2381,
          "name": "Pavel Paroulek",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pavel.paroulek@orange.com",
          "username": "wageslave"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-09-11 10:49:06.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHarish - to be clear what I mean by drawbacks - the current AAF settings force clients to 1. have an open VPN connection to the Windriver lab and 2. they need to have a properly configure ONAP DNS or add host entries to their machine(s).",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "792f9f50f8402ae33525601098feefbe5f236a51",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 33,
          "name": "James Forsyth",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jf2512@att.com",
          "username": "jimmydot"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-09-11 13:08:06.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n@Pavel, I think we need to leave the AAF setting off by default until we have done a successful pairwise test with an AAF that's been bootstrapped with AAI authorization info.  If we have it on by default, we would be breaking the weekly auto re-deploy of the HEAT env.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
